#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:9
#, no-c-format
msgid "Connecting and Authorizing"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:16
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Managing several &vmhost;s, each hosting multiple &vmguest;s, quickly "
"becomes difficult. One benefit of &libvirt; is the ability to connect to "
"several &vmhost;s at once, providing a single interface to manage all "
"&vmguest;s and to connect to their graphical console."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:22
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To ensure only authorized users can connect, &libvirt; offers several "
"connection types (via TLS, SSH, Unix sockets, and TCP) that can be combined "
"with different authorization mechanisms (socket, &pk;, SASL and Kerberos)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:29
#, no-c-format
msgid "Authentication"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:31
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The power to manage &vmguest;s and to access their graphical console is "
"something that should be restricted to a well defined circle of persons. To "
"achieve this goal, you can use the following authentication techniques on "
"the &vmhost;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:40
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Access control for Unix sockets with permissions and group ownership. This "
"method is available for &libvirtd; connections only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:46
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Access control for Unix sockets with &pk;. This method is available for "
"local &libvirtd; connections only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"User name and password authentication with SASL (Simple Authentication and "
"Security Layer). This method is available for both, &libvirtd; and VNC "
"connections. Using SASL does not require real user accounts on the server, "
"since it uses its own database to store user names and passwords. "
"Connections authenticated with SASL are encrypted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:61
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Kerberos authentication. This method, available for &libvirtd; connections "
"only, is not covered in this manual. Refer to <link xlink:href=\"http://"
"libvirt.org/auth.html#ACL_server_kerberos\"></link> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:69
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Single password authentication. This method is available for VNC connections "
"only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:77
#, no-c-format
msgid "Authentication for &libvirtd; and VNC need to be configured separately"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:78
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Access to the &vmguest;'s management functions (via &libvirtd;) on the one "
"hand, and to its graphical console on the other hand, always needs to be "
"configured separately. When restricting access to the management tools, "
"these restrictions do <emphasis>not</emphasis> automatically apply to VNC "
"connections!"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:87
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When accessing &vmguest;s from remote via TLS/SSL connections, access can be "
"indirectly controlled on each client by restricting read permissions to the "
"certificate's key file to a certain group. See <xref linkend=\"sec.libvirt."
"connect.remote.tls.security\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:95
#, no-c-format
msgid "&libvirtd; Authentication"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:96
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&libvirtd; authentication is configured in <filename>/etc/libvirt/libvirtd."
"conf</filename>. The configuration made here applies to all &libvirt; tools "
"such as the &vmm; or <command>virsh</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:102
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&libvirt; offers two sockets: a read-only socket for monitoring purposes and "
"a read-write socket to be used for management operations. Access to both "
"sockets can be configured independently. By default, both sockets are owned "
"by <literal>root.root</literal>. Default access permissions on the read-"
"write socket are restricted to the user &rootuser; (<literal>0700</literal>) "
"and fully open on the read-only socket (<literal>0777</literal>)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:111
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In the following instructions, you will learn how to configure access "
"permissions for the read-write socket. The same instructions also apply to "
"the read-only socket. All configuration steps need to be carried out on the "
"&vmhost;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:118
#, no-c-format
msgid "Default Authentication Settings on &productname;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:119
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The default authentication method on &productname; is access control for "
"Unix sockets. Only the user &rootuser; may authenticate. When accessing the "
"&libvirt; tools as a non-root user directly on the &vmhost;, you need to "
"provide the &rootuser; password through &pk; once. You are then granted "
"access for the current and for future sessions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:127
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can configure &libvirt; to allow <quote>system</quote> "
"access to non-privileged users. See <xref linkend=\"sec.libvirt.connect."
"connecting.dac\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:134
#, no-c-format
msgid "Recommended Authorization Methods"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_connect.xml:136
#, no-c-format
msgid "Local Connections"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_connect.xml:147
#, no-c-format
msgid "Remote Tunnel over SSH"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_connect.xml:156
#, no-c-format
msgid "Remote TLS/SSL Connection"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: member
#: libvirt_connect.xml:161
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"none (access controlled on the client side by restricting access to the "
"certificates)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:168
#, no-c-format
msgid "Access Control for Unix Sockets with Permissions and Group Ownership"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:169
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To grant access for non-&rootuser; accounts, configure the sockets to be "
"owned and accessible by a certain group (<systemitem class=\"groupname"
"\">libvirt</systemitem> in the following example). This authentication "
"method can be used for local and remote SSH connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:178
#, no-c-format
msgid "In case it does not exist, create the group that should own the socket:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:182
#, no-c-format
msgid "groupadd libvirt"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:184
#, no-c-format
msgid "Group Needs to Exist"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:185
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The group must exist prior to restarting &libvirtd;. If not, the restart "
"will fail."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:192
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the desired users to the group:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:195
#, no-c-format
msgid "usermod --append --groups libvirt &exampleuser_plain;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:198 libvirt_connect.xml:314
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Change the configuration in <filename>/etc/libvirt/libvirtd.conf</filename> "
"as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:202
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"unix_sock_group = \"libvirt\"<co xml:id=\"co.libvirt.connect.ssh.group\"/>\n"
"unix_sock_rw_perms = \"0770\"<co xml:id=\"co.libvirt.connect.ssh.perms\"/>\n"
"auth_unix_rw = \"none\"<co xml:id=\"co.libvirt.connect.ssh.enable\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:205
#, no-c-format
msgid "Group ownership will be set to group <literal>libvirt</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:210
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Sets the access permissions for the socket (<literal>srwxrwx---</literal>)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:216
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Disables other authentication methods (&pk; or SASL). Access is solely "
"controlled by the socket permissions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:224 libvirt_connect.xml:334 libvirt_connect.xml:494
#: libvirt_connect.xml:550 libvirt_connect.xml:600 libvirt_connect.xml:814
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restart &libvirtd;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:227
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemctl start libvirtd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:232
#, no-c-format
msgid "Local Access Control for Unix Sockets with &pk;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:233
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Access control for Unix sockets with &pk; is the default authentication "
"method on &productname; for non-remote connections. Therefore, no &libvirt; "
"configuration changes are needed. With &pk; authorization enabled, "
"permissions on both sockets default to <literal>0777</literal> and each "
"application trying to access a socket needs to authenticate via &pk;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:242
#, no-c-format
msgid "&pk; Authentication for Local Connections Only"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:243
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Authentication with &pk; can only be used for local connections on the "
"&vmhost; itself, since &pk; does not handle remote authentication."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:250
#, no-c-format
msgid "Two policies for accessing &libvirt;'s sockets exist:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:255
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<emphasis>org.libvirt.unix.monitor</emphasis>: accessing the read-only socket"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<emphasis>org.libvirt.unix.manage</emphasis>: accessing the read-write socket"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:267
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"By default, the policy for accessing the read-write socket is to "
"authenticate with the &rootuser; password once and grant the privilege for "
"the current and for future sessions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:272
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To grant users access to a socket without having to provide the &rootuser; "
"password, you need to create a rule in <filename>/etc/polkit-1/rules.d</"
"filename>. Create the file <filename>/etc/polkit-1/rules.d/10-grant-libvirt</"
"filename> with the following content to grant access to the read-write "
"socket to all members of the group <systemitem class=\"groupname\">libvirt</"
"systemitem>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:281
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"polkit.addRule(function(action, subject) {\n"
"  if (action.id == \"org.libvirt.unix.manage\" &amp;&amp; subject."
"isInGroup(\"libvirt\")) {\n"
"    return polkit.Result.YES;\n"
"  }\n"
"});"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:284 libvirt_connect.xml:424
#, no-c-format
msgid "User name and Password Authentication with SASL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:285
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SASL provides user name and password authentication and data encryption "
"(digest-md5, by default). Since SASL maintains its own user database, the "
"users do not need to exist on the &vmhost;. SASL is required by TCP "
"connections and on top of TLS/SSL connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:292
#, no-c-format
msgid "Plain TCP and SASL with digest-md5 Encryption"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:293
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using digest-md5 encryption on an otherwise not encrypted TCP connection "
"does not provide enough security for production environments. It is "
"recommended to only use it in testing environments."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:300
#, no-c-format
msgid "SASL Authentication on Top of TLS/SSL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:301
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Access from remote TLS/SSL connections can be indirectly controlled on the "
"<emphasis>client side</emphasis> by restricting access to the certificate's "
"key file. However, this might prove error-prone when dealing with many "
"clients. Using SASL with TLS adds security by additionally controlling "
"access on the server side."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:309
#, no-c-format
msgid "To configure SASL authentication, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:320
#, no-c-format
msgid "To enable SASL for TCP connections:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:323
#, no-c-format
msgid "auth_tcp = \"sasl\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:326
#, no-c-format
msgid "To enable SASL for TLS/SSL connections:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:329
#, no-c-format
msgid "auth_tls = \"sasl\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:337 libvirt_connect.xml:497
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemctl restart libvirtd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:340
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The libvirt SASL configuration file is located at <filename>/etc/sasl2/"
"libvirtd.conf</filename>. Normally, there is no need to change the defaults. "
"However, if using SASL on top of TLS, you may turn off session encryption to "
"avoid additional overhead (TLS connections are already encrypted) by "
"commenting the line setting the <literal>mech_list</literal> parameter. Only "
"do this for TSL/SASL, for TCP connections this parameter must be set to "
"digest-md5."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:349
#, no-c-format
msgid "#mech_list: digest-md5"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:352 libvirt_connect.xml:468
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"By default, no SASL users are configured, so no logins are possible. Use the "
"following commands to manage users:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_connect.xml:358 libvirt_connect.xml:474
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the user &exampleuser;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:360
#, no-c-format
msgid "saslpasswd2 -a libvirt &exampleuser_plain;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_connect.xml:364 libvirt_connect.xml:480
#, no-c-format
msgid "Delete the user &exampleuser;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:366
#, no-c-format
msgid "saslpasswd2 -a libvirt -d &exampleuser_plain;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_connect.xml:370 libvirt_connect.xml:486
#, no-c-format
msgid "List existing users"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:372
#, no-c-format
msgid "sasldblistusers2 -f /etc/libvirt/passwd.db"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:379
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>virsh</command> and SASL Authentication"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:380
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When using SASL authentication, you will be prompted for a user name and "
"password every time you issue a <command>virsh</command> command. Avoid this "
"by using <command>virsh</command> in shell mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:390
#, no-c-format
msgid "VNC Authentication"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:391
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Since access to the graphical console of a &vmguest; is not controlled by "
"&libvirt;, but rather by the specific hypervisor, it is always necessary to "
"additionally configure VNC authentication. The main configuration file is "
"<filename>/etc/libvirt/&lt;hypervisor&gt;.conf</filename>. This section "
"describes the &qemu;/&kvm; hypervisor, so the target configuration file is "
"<filename>/etc/libvirt/qemu.conf</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:401
#, no-c-format
msgid "VNC Authentication for &xen;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:402
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In contrast to &kvm; and &lxc;, &xen; does not yet offer more sophisticated "
"VNC authentication than setting a password on a per VM basis. See the "
"<literal>&lt;graphics type='vnc'...</literal> &libvirt; configuration option "
"below."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:409
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Two authentication types are available: SASL and single password "
"authentication. If you are using SASL for &libvirt; authentication, it is "
"strongly recommended to use it for VNC authentication as well&mdash;it is "
"possible to share the same database."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:415
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A third method to restrict access to the &vmguest; is to enable the use of "
"TLS encryption on the VNC server. This requires the VNC clients to have "
"access to x509 client certificates. By restricting access to these "
"certificates, access can indirectly be controlled on the client side. Refer "
"to <xref linkend=\"sec.libvirt.connect.remote.tls.vnc.client\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:425
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SASL provides user name and password authentication and data encryption. "
"Since SASL maintains its own user database, the users do not need to exist "
"on the &vmhost;. As with SASL authentication for &libvirt;, you may use SASL "
"on top of TLS/SSL connections. Refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.libvirt.connect."
"remote.tls.vnc.client\"/> for details on configuring these connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:433
#, no-c-format
msgid "To configure SASL authentication for VNC, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:438
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Create a SASL configuration file. It is recommended to use the existing "
"&libvirt; file. If you have already configured SASL for &libvirt; and are "
"planning to use the same settings including the same user name and password "
"database, a simple link is suitable:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:444
#, no-c-format
msgid "ln -s /etc/sasl2/libvirt.conf /etc/sasl2/qemu.conf"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:445
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If are setting up SASL for VNC only or you are planning to use a different "
"configuration than for &libvirt;, copy the existing file to use as a "
"template:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:450
#, no-c-format
msgid "cp /etc/sasl2/libvirt.conf /etc/sasl2/qemu.conf"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:451
#, no-c-format
msgid "Then edit it according to your needs."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:456 libvirt_connect.xml:538
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Change the configuration in <filename>/etc/libvirt/qemu.conf</filename> as "
"follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:460
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"vnc_listen = \"0.0.0.0\"\n"
"vnc_sasl = 1\n"
"sasldb_path: /etc/libvirt/qemu_passwd.db"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:461
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The first parameter enables VNC to listen on all public interfaces (rather "
"than to the local host only), and the second parameter enables SASL "
"authentication."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:476
#, no-c-format
msgid "saslpasswd2 -f /etc/libvirt/qemu_passwd.db -a qemu &exampleuser_plain;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:482
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"saslpasswd2 -f /etc/libvirt/qemu_passwd.db -a qemu -d &exampleuser_plain;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:488
#, no-c-format
msgid "sasldblistusers2 -f /etc/libvirt/qemu_passwd.db"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:500
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Restart all &vmguest;s that have been running prior to changing the "
"configuration. &vmguest;s that have not been restarted will not use SASL "
"authentication for VNC connects."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:508
#, no-c-format
msgid "Supported VNC Viewers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:509
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SASL authentication is currently supported by &vmm; and <command>virt-"
"viewer</command>. Both of these viewers also support TLS/SSL connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:517
#, no-c-format
msgid "Single Password Authentication"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Access to the VNC server may also be controlled by setting a VNC password. "
"You can either set a global password for all &vmguest;s or set individual "
"passwords for each guest. The latter requires to edit the &vmguest;'s "
"configuration files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:525
#, no-c-format
msgid "Always Set a Global Password"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you are using single password authentication, it is good practice to set "
"a global password even if setting passwords for each &vmguest;. This will "
"always leave your virtual machines protected with a <quote>fallback</quote> "
"password if you forget to set a per-machine password. The global password "
"will only be used if no other password is set for the machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting a Global VNC Password"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:542
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"vnc_listen = \"0.0.0.0\"\n"
"vnc_password = \"<replaceable>PASSWORD</replaceable>\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:543
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The first parameter enables VNC to listen on all public interfaces (rather "
"than to the local host only), and the second parameter sets the password. "
"The maximum length of the password is eight characters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:553 libvirt_connect.xml:603 libvirt_connect.xml:817
#: libvirt_connect.xml:1033 libvirt_connect.xml:1137 libvirt_connect.xml:1329
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;systemctl restart libvirtd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:556 libvirt_connect.xml:606
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Restart all &vmguest;s that have been running prior to changing the "
"configuration. &vmguest;s that have not been restarted will not use password "
"authentication for VNC connects."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_connect.xml:564
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting a &vmguest; Specific VNC Password"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Change the configuration in <filename>/etc/libvirt/qemu.conf</filename> as "
"follows to enable VNC to listen on all public interfaces (rather than to the "
"local host only)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:572
#, no-c-format
msgid "vnc_listen = \"0.0.0.0\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:575
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Open the &vmguest;'s XML configuration file in an editor. Replace "
"<replaceable>VM NAME</replaceable> in the following example with the name of "
"the &vmguest;. The editor that is used defaults to <envar>$EDITOR</envar>. "
"If that variable is not set, <command>vi</command> is used."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_connect.xml:582
#, no-c-format
msgid "virsh edit <replaceable>VM NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_connect.xml:585
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Search for the element <literal>&lt;graphics&gt;</literal> with the "
"attribute <literal>type='vnc'</literal>, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
